temp.fibHeap.stixar.util
Class CList<T>

java.lang.Object
  temp.fibHeap.stixar.util.CList<T>
All Implemented Interfaces:
java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable, java.lang.Iterable<T>, java.util.Collection<T>, java.util.List<T>, java.util.Queue<T>
public class CList<T>
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.util.List<T>, java.util.Queue<T>, java.lang.Cloneable, java.io.Serializable

This class is just like a java LinkedList, except ...

  • It exposes the list nodes so that the programmer can more easily efficiently store locations of the list for later retrieval and make threaded data structures on top of lists.
  • offers some additional constant time list operations such as concatenation and removal via a cell.

It is more or less completely interoperable with java.util.LinkedList, with the following exceptions:

  • clear() does not take O(n) time, it is constant time and depends on the garbage collector to deal with the cyclic references.

It is called CList because it exposes the list cells to the programmer.

This is not synchronized. If multiple threads are to access this list, use Collections.synchronizedList().

Although, as in java.util.LinkedList, the iterators make a best effort at fail-fast commodification detection, the programmer may perform commodification when iterating via the ListCells, so long as no plain Iterator is iterating over the list.

remove

public final T remove(ListCell<T> cell)
Remove the element with cell cell from this list.

This is a constant time operation.

Note: While a check is made in an attempt to verify that cell belongs to this list, the check may not succeed if the this list was constructed in part by the append(CList) or the prepend(CList) methods. If these methods are are not used, an IllegalArgumentException is guaranteed to be thrown if the cell does not belong to this list. Otherwise, if cell does not belong to this list, either IllegalArgumentException is thrown or the list becomes corrupt, indicating the wrong size.

Parameters:
cell - the list cell to be removed from this list.

append

public final void append(CList<T> list)
Destroy list by making it the end of this list. At the end of this method, list is empty and its elements are concatenated to the end of this list. The operation takes constant time.

Warning

Use of this method is likely to reduce the efficacy of the fail-fast-ness of the iterators and the efficacy of checks when removing by list cell.

Throws:
java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if called with this.append(this);
